  "passageParts": [
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": "Why do people read negative Internet comments and do other things that will obviously be painful? Because humans have an inherent need to\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 1
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nuncertainty, according to a recent study in Psychological Science. The new research reveals that the need to know is so strong that people will\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 2
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto satisfy their curiosity even when it is learnt the answer will\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 3
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​.\n In a series of experiments, behavioral scientists at the University of Chicago and the Wisconsin school of Business tested students' willingness to\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 4
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthemselves to unpleasant stimuli in an effort to satisfy curiosity. For one\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 5
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​, each participant was shown a pile of pens that the researcher claimed were from a previous experiment. The twist? Half of the pens would\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 6
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nan electric shock when clicked.\n Twenty-seven students were told which pens were electrified; another twenty-seven were told only that some were electrified.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 7
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nleft alone in the room, the students who did not know which ones would shock them clicked more pens and incurred more shocks than the students who knew what would\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 8
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​. Subsequent experiments reproduced this effect with other stimuli,\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 9
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthe sound of fingernails on a chalkboard and photographs of disgusting insects.\n The drive to\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 10
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nis deeply rooted in humans, much the same as the basic drives for\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 11
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nor shelter, says Christopher Hsee of the University of Chicago. \"Curiosity is often considered a good instinct—it can\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 12
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nnew scientific advances, for instance—but sometimes such\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 13
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\ncan backfire. The insight that curiosity can drive you to do\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 14
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nthings is a profound one.\"\n Unhealthy curiosity is possible to\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 15
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​, however. In a final experiment, participants who were encouraged to\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 16
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nhow they would feel after viewing an unpleasant picture were less likely to\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 17
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nto see such an image. These results suggest that imagining the\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 18
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nof following through on one's curiosity ahead of time can help determine\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 19
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nit is worth the endeavor. \"Thinking about long-term\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "blank",
      "blankId": 20
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "content": " ​\nis key to reducing the possible negative effects of curiosity,\" Hsee says. In other words, don't read online comments."
    }
  ],
